article.headline: Western Kentucky 71, Georgia 61
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Antonio Haynes scored 16 of his 20 points in the first half and Western Kentucky pulled away at the end for a 71-61 victory over Georgia, ruining coach Dennis Felton's first game against his former team. The Bulldogs (0-1) closed to 60-57 with 5½ minutes remaining on back-to-back 3-pointers by Sundiata Gaines and Channing Toney. But Western Kentucky (2-0) scored the next seven points to finish off the Bulldogs. Anthony Winchester scored on a lay-in, Courtney Lee finished off a fast break with a dunk, then Lee made three free throws after being fouled on a shot outside the arc. Felton coached the Hilltoppers for five years, compiling a 100-54 record and winning the Sun Belt Conference championship each of his last three years. As part of his buyout to replace Jim Harrick at Georgia, Felton agreed to a four-year series with his former school. This was the first game in that deal -- and certainly a good time for Western Kentucky to face the Bulldogs. Felton has only one returning starter from last season, and he played just 12 minutes. Levi Stukes was plagued by foul trouble, managing five points. The Bulldogs have only seven players on scholarship. Tommy Wainscott, who made the team during tryouts at the student athletic center last month, played 14 minutes and scored four points. Haynes dominated the first half. He hit 7 of 10 from the field, including a couple of 3-pointers. Georgia shut down the senior guard in the second half, but Lee stepped up to fill the void. He had all but two of his 14 points after the break. Winchester had 17 for the Hilltoppers, and Ty Rogers added 10. Gaines, a freshman point guard, paced Georgia with 17 points. Toney, also a freshman, chipped in with 10 points, and yet another freshman, Dave Bliss, grabbed 10 rebounds.
